1
00:01:07,745 --> 00:01:09,107
When shall I pick you up, sir?

2
00:01:11,501 --> 00:01:14,648
Give me time for a couple of cocktails.
Say, half an hour.           - Yes, sir.

3
00:01:14,938 --> 00:01:17,999
Mrs Farnsworth asks me to remind you
you have a dinner engagement tonight.

4
00:01:18,375 --> 00:01:20,816
Well, a half-hour will just give
me time to change and make it.

5
00:01:21,396 --> 00:01:24,713
By the way .. did Mrs Farnsworth
mention with whom we are dining?

6
00:01:24,929 --> 00:01:28,093
With the Lindens, sir.
- Oh, the Lindens.

7
00:01:29,459 --> 00:01:31,406
You'd better make it an hour, Williams.

8
00:01:31,826 --> 00:01:34,645
I find I'll need more
cocktails than I thought.

9
00:01:47,484 --> 00:01:50,620
I beg your pardon .. but
aren't you Joyce Heath?

10
00:01:51,982 --> 00:01:53,372
No.
- But I ..

11
00:01:53,860 --> 00:01:55,024
You've made a mistake.

12
00:01:57,517 --> 00:02:00,080
Perhaps I have .. pardon me.

13
00:02:10,925 --> 00:02:11,855
Gentlemen.

14
00:02:12,193 --> 00:02:14,353
How are you Mr Farnsworth?
- Evening, Roger.

15
00:02:15,517 --> 00:02:18,907
Anthony, a Sidecar, with just a
splash more brandy than necessary.

16
00:02:19,648 --> 00:02:22,690
I suppose you know what brandy
does to your liver, Roger.

17
00:02:22,962 --> 00:02:25,348
Yes. That's why I stopped
port and turned to brandy.

18
00:02:25,564 --> 00:02:28,221
Your liver is far less
conspicuous than your nose.

19
00:02:29,443 --> 00:02:31,715
Do you chaps remember
an actress Joyce Heath?

20
00:02:32,250 --> 00:02:35,379
I'll never forget her
as Camille .. Sappho.

21
00:02:35,586 --> 00:02:37,678
I saw her only once,
but I'll never forget her.

22
00:02:38,344 --> 00:02:40,872
What a vitally tempestuous
creature she was.

23
00:02:41,435 --> 00:02:44,795
It's amazing how powerfully a personality
can project itself across the footlights.

24
00:02:45,639 --> 00:02:47,439
That night I was in
the rear of the theater.

25
00:02:47,618 --> 00:02:49,827
Yet couldn't have been closer
if I'd held her in my arms.

26
00:02:49,956 --> 00:02:51,705
Not closer perhaps,
but more interesting.

27
00:02:52,040 --> 00:02:54,418
Quiet .. let the gentleman confess.

28
00:02:54,707 --> 00:02:55,965
Joyce Heath never knew it.

29
00:02:56,162 --> 00:02:59,442
But she prompted me to make a decision
that changed the course of my whole life.

30
00:03:00,985 --> 00:03:04,385
The career my family planned for
me in Wall Street I discarded.

31
00:03:04,938 --> 00:03:06,995
I suddenly got the urge to create.

32
00:03:07,427 --> 00:03:10,319
I gave up writing as I couldn't write,
and music because I couldn't play.

33
00:03:10,460 --> 00:03:11,746
But I could draw ..

34
00:03:12,271 --> 00:03:14,007
Three years in Paris taught me ..

35
00:03:14,833 --> 00:03:16,684
Not defeat .. but compromise.

36
00:03:17,434 --> 00:03:19,821
I still had enough of the urge
left to try architecture.

37
00:03:20,430 --> 00:03:23,032
I saw her tonight, just as I came in.

38
00:03:23,446 --> 00:03:26,983
Dowdy, down and out .. and
ashamed of being Joyce Heath.

39
00:03:27,621 --> 00:03:28,946
She was tops.

40
00:03:30,204 --> 00:03:32,438
What's the matter, Mr Hanley?
Isn't the Highball right?

41
00:03:32,692 --> 00:03:36,607
Oh .. the Highball. Yes, perfect .. why?

42
00:03:36,832 --> 00:03:39,623
Well, you looked as if
something tasted or smelt bad.

43
00:03:39,989 --> 00:03:42,797
I would rather you wouldn't mention
that. I was reading my own column.

44
00:03:43,405 --> 00:03:45,321
Ted.
- Yeah?

45
00:03:45,771 --> 00:03:47,149
We want to ask you something.

46
00:03:47,940 --> 00:03:49,574
Yes, it's a toupee.

47
00:03:51,628 --> 00:03:54,316
What about Joyce Heath? She was a star.

48
00:03:55,179 --> 00:03:57,842
She was too brilliant.
Too startling for a star.

49
00:03:58,194 --> 00:04:00,612
She was a comet, which
appeared suddenly ..

50
00:04:00,837 --> 00:04:03,602
Fell spectacularly, and
disappeared completely.

51
00:04:04,100 --> 00:04:08,030
That gentlemen, is a metaphor. One of
the great actresses .. and Joyce Heath.

52
00:04:08,227 --> 00:04:10,963
That's why I can't read his
column. He writes that way, too.

53
00:04:11,908 --> 00:04:13,443
Yes, but what happened to her, Ted?

54
00:04:13,588 --> 00:04:16,959
Fantastic as it may sound .. a jinx.
One she put on other people.

55
00:04:17,311 --> 00:04:18,213
A jinx?

56
00:04:18,551 --> 00:04:21,530
It started when her leading man
was killed on an opening night.

57
00:04:22,290 --> 00:04:27,107
From then on .. everyone associated with
her was haunted by failures, divorces ..

58
00:04:27,586 --> 00:04:28,732
Suicides and scandals.

59
00:04:28,910 --> 00:04:31,765
That's right. She practically
lived on the front page.

60
00:04:32,365 --> 00:04:35,715
At first, she laughed at the
superstition .. then she believed it.

61
00:04:36,470 --> 00:04:39,274
Last time I saw her, she was
on a cheap Vaudeville tour.

62
00:04:39,771 --> 00:04:42,827
Then she vanished.
Like the magician's lady.

63
00:04:44,432 --> 00:04:46,169
Sounds almost unbelievable, doesn't it.

64
00:04:47,770 --> 00:04:48,883
But it happened.

65
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,365
Well, I've got to break into a trot if I
want to change and pick up Gail in time.

66
00:04:55,681 --> 00:04:57,398
We have a dinner date.
- The Lindens?

67
00:04:57,849 --> 00:04:58,788
The Lindens.

68
00:04:58,995 --> 00:05:02,200
I think they get most of their guests
from the tomb of Ramses The Second.

69
00:05:02,722 --> 00:05:05,042
There's quite a few valuable
Civil-War relics among them, too.

70
00:05:05,712 --> 00:05:06,904
Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

71
00:05:07,078 --> 00:05:08,129
A clever boy, that.

72
00:05:08,229 --> 00:05:10,012
One of the best architects
in the country.

73
00:05:10,112 --> 00:05:13,712
With his reputation and Gail Armitage
connections, he'll come out alright.

74
00:05:14,217 --> 00:05:17,270
By the way, when are they to be married?
- It hasn't been arranged, yet.

75
00:05:17,634 --> 00:05:18,610
How do you know?

76
00:05:19,005 --> 00:05:22,810
Mrs Farnsworth hasn't heard.
- Maybe they're keeping it a secret?

77
00:05:23,317 --> 00:05:25,317
What, from my wife? Impossible.

78
00:05:36,876 --> 00:05:38,455
Good evening, Cato.
- Good evening.

79
00:05:40,009 --> 00:05:43,813
I'm late, Cato. You'd better draw me a
bath, lay out my dinner jacket and ..

80
00:05:44,133 --> 00:05:45,439
Never mind the bath.

81
00:05:45,766 --> 00:05:49,157
Did you ever try putting celluloid fish
in the tub to entice him into it, Cato?

82
00:05:49,570 --> 00:05:51,138
Gail, what are you doing here?

83
00:05:51,345 --> 00:05:54,424
I finished early, so I came over to save
you the trouble of driving out to get me.

84
00:05:54,707 --> 00:05:55,974
Good for you.

85
00:05:56,958 --> 00:05:59,417
Uh, Cato .. stew up a cocktail.

86
00:06:00,019 --> 00:06:01,549
I don't want a cocktail, thank you.

87
00:06:01,868 --> 00:06:04,901
Well, some hors d'oeuvres, Cato.
- They always spoil my dinner.

88
00:06:05,888 --> 00:06:09,345
Cato, you fix the young lady a ham
sandwich whether she wants it or not.

89
00:06:14,330 --> 00:06:16,373
Gail, what do you think?
- That I love you.

90
00:06:16,542 --> 00:06:18,382
Well, I'm pretty fond of
myself this evening.

91
00:06:18,514 --> 00:06:20,429
The bank is going to
make the building loan.

92
00:06:20,673 --> 00:06:23,236
Don, how marvelous!
- Miraculous is the word.

93
00:06:23,415 --> 00:06:25,743
All I have to do is put a
hundred thousand in escrow.

94
00:06:26,044 --> 00:06:27,781
But they could let you
have the land now.

95
00:06:27,978 --> 00:06:30,353
Don't worry about the petty cash.
It will come out alright.

96
00:06:30,691 --> 00:06:33,930
Think of starting on those estates,
after dreaming about them for years.

97
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:35,911
I know exactly how
they're going to look.

98
00:06:36,090 --> 00:06:39,301
Unless I fall down, they'll be the most
beautiful estates in the whole country.

99
00:06:40,072 --> 00:06:43,888
And I can't fall down. I've worked too
hard, I've waited too long to flop.

100
00:06:44,384 --> 00:06:46,729
It seems as though it's all going
to come through, doesn't it.

101
00:06:47,809 --> 00:06:51,343
I guess we have everything, young lady.
- And best of all, we have us.

102
00:06:51,935 --> 00:06:53,231
Ham sandwich please.

103
00:06:57,052 --> 00:06:59,221
No mustard.
- No mustard?

104
00:06:59,558 --> 00:07:01,944
No mustard.
- Cato, go look for some mustard.

105
00:07:02,257 --> 00:07:05,590
If you find any and bring it here, you'll
go out of here looking like a hot-dog.

106
00:07:09,391 --> 00:07:11,928
Happy?
- Ecstatically.          - Why?

107
00:07:12,218 --> 00:07:17,509
Because dear, I have a very good sense.
- You ineffable cad, you.

108
00:07:18,142 --> 00:07:20,210
You adorable darling, you.

109
00:07:22,487 --> 00:07:24,893
You must hurry and get dressed
or we'll be late for the Lindens.

110
00:07:25,081 --> 00:07:27,823
Can't we get out of it somehow?
- No, we cannot.

111
00:07:28,026 --> 00:07:30,515
You'll meet a lot of people there
who can afford to buy your houses.

112
00:07:30,725 --> 00:07:33,929
People who go to the Lindens don't
need houses, they need tombs.

113
00:07:44,180 --> 00:07:46,246
[ meow ]

114
00:07:47,443 --> 00:07:50,213
[ woof, woof ]

115
00:07:54,661 --> 00:07:56,518
Gail and I couldn't stand it any longer.

116
00:07:56,750 --> 00:08:00,774
Being the extra man at a Linden party
is like being a spare corpse at a wake.

117
00:08:01,245 --> 00:08:03,130
I could kiss you for
getting us out of there.

118
00:08:03,416 --> 00:08:06,186
I could too, if you didn't look so much
like a horse that threw me once.

119
00:08:06,844 --> 00:08:08,980
Be exact. There have been so many.

120
00:08:09,599 --> 00:08:12,440
Delightful women you take
up with. What shall we do?

121
00:08:12,780 --> 00:08:15,104
You know what I'd like to do?
- Steal a water melon?

122
00:08:15,444 --> 00:08:17,289
Paint moustaches on a library lion.

123
00:08:17,522 --> 00:08:20,104
One of you are bound to say
something rude if this goes on.

124
00:08:20,506 --> 00:08:23,052
I'd like to go to the shooting
galleries and Honky-Tonks and things.

125
00:08:23,287 --> 00:08:24,357
An idea.

126
00:08:25,065 --> 00:08:27,513
I'll send my driver home,
and we'll all go in your car.

127
00:08:27,700 --> 00:08:30,821
No you won't. I've got a tough day
tomorrow. I want to get up early.

128
00:08:31,034 --> 00:08:34,835
I don't want to spend tonight escorting
you in, and carrying you out of a club.

129
00:08:35,095 --> 00:08:37,530
Say, listen. I've never been
carried to any place in my life.

130
00:08:38,123 --> 00:08:41,108
Thrown, yes .. but carried, never.

131
00:09:06,209 --> 00:09:10,011
Come on, let's not go home. Let's go
in there and try some bird's nest soup.

132
00:09:10,258 --> 00:09:12,453
How about a little high
class sharp-shooting?

133
00:09:12,857 --> 00:09:15,002
A harbor for flotsam and
jetsam. A bit of O'Henry's.

134
00:09:15,322 --> 00:09:16,392
You win.

135
00:09:28,015 --> 00:09:31,238
A smart looking place.
- Who's idea was this?

136
00:09:32,346 --> 00:09:33,719
You can sit here.

137
00:09:34,224 --> 00:09:36,083
I guess we'd better stand at the bar.

138
00:09:36,806 --> 00:09:39,143
You'd better sit where
he tells you to, dear.

139
00:10:01,237 --> 00:10:03,994
Oh Don, this is such a depressing place.
- You don't want to stay?

140
00:10:04,300 --> 00:10:06,237
No, let's get out of here. Come on.

141
00:10:09,229 --> 00:10:10,914
Some other time.

142
00:10:16,956 --> 00:10:19,635
Well, you can chalk one up against
me. I certainly can pick them.

143
00:10:20,809 --> 00:10:22,085
Now where?

144
00:10:23,247 --> 00:10:25,583
Oh, it's after 12 o'clock.
Don's got to get to bed.

145
00:10:25,853 --> 00:10:28,001
He's been working like a Trojan lately.

146
00:10:28,353 --> 00:10:31,290
Why don't you go on with Teddy.
Let him take you home.

147
00:10:32,490 --> 00:10:34,676
It would save me an hour,
getting out and back.

148
00:10:35,075 --> 00:10:36,124
Do you mind, Teddy?

149
00:10:36,378 --> 00:10:39,486
No, not if he don't talk about Don.
- Alright. Why don't you do it then?

150
00:10:39,805 --> 00:10:43,627
I think I will. I've an early meeting in
the morning. I'll call you after that.

151
00:10:44,002 --> 00:10:45,469
Don't forget.
- No.

152
00:10:45,680 --> 00:10:48,427
Listen, you're coming to the club to
see me play Polo next week aren't you?

153
00:10:48,603 --> 00:10:52,312
Well, you mean to see the horse
play and you get tired? I might.

154
00:10:52,941 --> 00:10:55,355
Goodnight.
- Goodnight, darling.

155
00:10:55,716 --> 00:10:57,242
Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

156
00:11:34,748 --> 00:11:36,514
Do you mind if I sit down?

157
00:11:37,405 --> 00:11:40,326
Not if you buy a drink.
- Two of whatever the lady is drinking.

158
00:11:40,667 --> 00:11:41,959
Straight gin.

159
00:11:47,320 --> 00:11:50,815
I've seen you before.
- Which doesn't make us old friends.

160
00:11:53,693 --> 00:11:55,148
Well you see, one time, I ..

161
00:11:55,383 --> 00:11:58,517
It really doesn't interest me,
if you don't mind.

162
00:12:02,336 --> 00:12:03,306
Thanks.

163
00:12:04,691 --> 00:12:05,745
Not at all.

164
00:12:09,031 --> 00:12:10,481
Rather ironical, isn't it?

165
00:12:12,401 --> 00:12:13,829
Are you going to drink that?

166
00:12:15,040 --> 00:12:16,298
Haven't you had enough?

167
00:12:18,858 --> 00:12:19,928
Quite enough.

168
00:12:27,762 --> 00:12:29,371
Goodnight Joyce Heath.

169
00:12:33,066 --> 00:12:35,813
What did you say?
- Joyce Heath.

170
00:12:37,128 --> 00:12:38,414
I ..

171
00:12:39,644 --> 00:12:41,400
Joyce Heath, the actress ..

172
00:12:41,735 --> 00:12:45,287
Sitting in a dive like this
swilling down cheap gin.

173
00:12:46,586 --> 00:12:48,112
You must be drunk, too.

174
00:12:48,476 --> 00:12:51,328
No, there isn't much similarity
except in appearance.

175
00:12:52,226 --> 00:12:54,005
Lots of people look alike.

176
00:12:54,479 --> 00:12:56,273
Joyce Heath was full of life.

177
00:12:57,108 --> 00:12:59,909
I'll never forget the time I saw
her. She was playing Juliet.

178
00:13:01,458 --> 00:13:06,150
Do you remember the scene where you
were told you had to marry Count Paris?

179
00:13:06,423 --> 00:13:10,045
And you took the sleeping draught to
pretend death until Romeo's return?

180
00:13:11,348 --> 00:13:14,019
As your mother kissed you
goodnight .. and left you.

181
00:13:15,090 --> 00:13:20,749
You began: "farewell, God knows
when we shall meet again".

182
00:13:21,483 --> 00:13:26,265
Farewell .. God knows
when we shall meet again.

183
00:13:28,517 --> 00:13:31,785
A faint, cold fear thrills my veins.

184
00:13:33,565 --> 00:13:36,630
And almost freezes out the heat of life.

185
00:13:40,282 --> 00:13:42,282
I shall call them back to comfort me.

186
00:13:44,598 --> 00:13:45,644
Nurse.

187
00:13:47,415 --> 00:13:49,071
What should she do here?

188
00:13:50,689 --> 00:13:53,645
My needs must act my dismal scene alone.

189
00:13:56,417 --> 00:13:57,738
Come vial.

190
00:13:59,926 --> 00:14:02,301
What if this mixture do not work?

191
00:14:03,764 --> 00:14:06,769
Shall I, by force, be
married to the Count?

192
00:14:08,388 --> 00:14:09,155
No.

193
00:14:11,193 --> 00:14:13,108
No .. this shall ..

194
00:14:14,562 --> 00:14:15,644
This shall ..

195
00:14:21,018 --> 00:14:22,076
Passed out?

196
00:14:23,447 --> 00:14:27,043
I'll call the wagon. They'll throw
her in the tank until the morning.

197
00:14:27,540 --> 00:14:28,639
Waiter.

198
00:14:30,407 --> 00:14:31,569
I'll take her home.

199
00:14:32,217 --> 00:14:35,689
Okay buddy. Pay me twenty cents
for them two drinks and she's yours.

200
00:14:40,631 --> 00:14:42,941
Keep the change, boss?
- Yes.

201
00:14:43,157 --> 00:14:44,199
Okay.

202
00:15:34,603 --> 00:15:36,469
[ door knocks ]

203
00:15:38,241 --> 00:15:39,075
Yes?

204
00:15:47,001 --> 00:15:48,183
You look poorly.

205
00:15:49,451 --> 00:15:53,069
Then it won't surprise you to be
told that I <i>feel</i> poorly.        - No.

206
00:15:53,671 --> 00:15:56,488
Figuring the moist condition
you arrived in last night.

207
00:15:57,099 --> 00:16:00,299
And just where did I arrive? I'm not
asking you to betray a confidence.

208
00:16:01,418 --> 00:16:04,300
This is Mr Bellows' place.
He's an architect.

209
00:16:04,995 --> 00:16:07,729
One of them fellows that draws pictures.
- Thank you.

210
00:16:08,786 --> 00:16:12,316
I suppose you are Mrs Bellows?
Or are you just one of his sketches?

211
00:16:12,861 --> 00:16:17,190
Nope .. I'm his housekeeper for when
he comes down here weekends.

212
00:16:18,234 --> 00:16:22,364
How cozy. And Mr Bellows, where is he?
- He's having breakfast.

213
00:16:22,912 --> 00:16:26,518
And if you want to see him, you better
look perky. He's got to get to town.

214
00:16:27,060 --> 00:16:29,412
I'm looking forward
to seeing Mr Bellows.

215
00:16:32,358 --> 00:16:33,760
Watch out.
- Leave me alone!

216
00:16:33,948 --> 00:16:36,652
No, I wasn't going to push you ..
- Do you mind leaving me alone!

217
00:16:36,793 --> 00:16:38,944
Nope .. in fact, I'd like it.

218
00:16:51,900 --> 00:16:53,237
Well, she's up.

219
00:16:54,570 --> 00:16:58,215
Oh .. I bet the Mahoney boys are
having a parade for her this morning.

220
00:16:58,600 --> 00:17:00,634
There wasn't no-one in her room.

221
00:17:01,150 --> 00:17:03,257
I don't know the Mahoney boys anyhow.

222
00:17:03,746 --> 00:17:06,534
You never heard of the Mahoney Boys?
You are very fortunate.

223
00:17:07,369 --> 00:17:11,886
They're little men with beards who play
tunes on your teeth with one hand ..

224
00:17:12,082 --> 00:17:14,354
And keep time with mallets
inside your head with the other.

225
00:17:14,661 --> 00:17:17,304
At the same time they run around your
stomach planting jumping beans.

226
00:17:18,140 --> 00:17:20,539
You wouldn't be pulling my
leg would you Mr Bellows?

227
00:17:21,079 --> 00:17:22,553
Please .. Mrs Williams.

228
00:17:41,005 --> 00:17:42,800
Feeling better?
- I'd like a drink.

229
00:17:44,130 --> 00:17:45,132
Before breakfast?

230
00:17:46,045 --> 00:17:47,195
Get me a drink!

231
00:17:59,469 --> 00:18:00,941
Why don't you lay off that stuff?

232
00:18:01,347 --> 00:18:02,965
Because I'd rather be drunk than sober.

233
00:18:03,147 --> 00:18:06,274
I gathered that last night.
- Last night?

